image.altText: A young boy smiles in front of a silo with a truck filling with grain.

props.synopsis: Jake is happiest when he's running around his small farming town and watching the trucks fill up with grain at the silo. The freedom has let his education flourish.

title.children: Jake is one of hundreds of children who experience school refusal. His mum has found a solution

image.altText: A woman holds her arm to her forehead while laying on a bed.

props.synopsis: Ads for products purporting to address the symptoms of menopause and perimenopause are flooding social media — but many of the claims "are not substantiated", a Senate inquiry is told.

title.children: Social media flooded by 'shameful' menopause product ads targeting women, inquiry hears

image.altText: A childhood educator sitting at a table with several young kids

props.synopsis: The federal government has announced it will fund a 15 per cent wage increase for early childhood education workers, tied to a commitment from childcare centres to limit fee increases.

title.children: Pay rise will help address staffing crisis in early childhood sector, providers say

image.altText: A middle aged man wearing glasses and a black jacket stares out a window

props.synopsis: Financial pressures following a work injury led to Brad Sullivan living in his car with his dog, Tasha. The experience left him feeling isolated, until he came across a community centre in the Adelaide Hills.

title.children: Loneliness project builds connections using cafe catch ups, board games and podcasts

image.altText: Tom Craig after being released from police custody in Paris.

props.synopsis: Paris public prosecutor's office confirms a 28-year-old Australian was arrested after being seen by police attempting to buy the illicit substance.

title.children: 'I've embarrassed you all': Australian hockey player Tom Craig arrested in Paris trying to buy cocaine

image.altText: A young gold retriever comes towards the camera with three other dogs playing in the background.

props.synopsis: Many breeds recognised as house dogs today were originally trained with specific tasks in mind. Has our long-running association with them taken away some of that independence and left them reliant on us in the long term?

title.children: Domesticated dogs seem to fit snugly into human lives, but are we harming them?

image.altText: A metal sign on a building saying YOUTH COURT

props.synopsis: A teenager accused of accessing extremist material on electronic devices owned by his school has been granted release on home detention bail and banned from using the internet.

title.children: Teen accused of possessing extremist material granted home detention bail

image.altText: A brick building behind a sign that reads "Mount Gambier Courthouse".

props.synopsis: A man from SA's South East is accused of leaving the scene of a crash that left a cyclist with broken ribs and a punctured lung.

title.children: Hit-and-run accused allegedly had child on lap, court hears

image.altText: over shoulder of young female artist doing dot painting on a large sculpture of an A

props.synopsis: What began as a way to preserve memories and explore her grief has blossomed into a thriving art career for Ceduna artist Jaylene Ware, joining the ranks of artists from a town known for its distinctive creative scene.

title.children: A confluence of land, sea, and desert country inspires Ceduna's thriving art scene

image.altText: A mother and child read a picture book while lying on a bed

props.synopsis: A Whyalla mother and first-time children's author hopes her book will break down the stigma around disability and help young families accept differences in the people around them.

title.children: Mum's picture book celebrates autistic son who 'climbs mountains' in his sleep

image.altText: A black-and-white photo of a runner with his coach.

props.synopsis: When running legend Herb Elliott won gold in 1960, he did so in a time that would have secured him a spot in the final at the Paris Olympics six decades later — and the sporting partnership that helped achieve that remarkable feat is now being celebrated on the silver screen.

title.children: Running uphill through sand, an eccentric visionary helped pave the path to gold

image.altText: Qantas CEO Alan Joyce speaks to the media during a press conference.

props.synopsis: Qantas has reduced former chief executive Alan Joyce's multi-million-dollar payout by almost $10 million.

image.altText: A smiling blond woman

image.altText: Soumia shields her eyes, smiling looking up at the sun for a story about being sun smart with darker skin

image.altText: A group of men wearing muslim garbs with khmanei in the middle looking over two coffins with the palestinian flag

props.synopsis: Israelis are on edge awaiting a response to two high profile assassinations, but Iran is facing a near-impossible task of calibrating what it should be.

title.children: Why hasn't Iran attacked Israel yet? It's scared, calculating or both

image.altText: Nina Kennedy pulls a determined face while holding an Australian flag

title.children: Overcoming her past demons, Nina Kennedy was the perfect person to lift Australia to its greatest ever Olympic heights

image.altText: Taylor Swift throws a hand in the air as she sings on stage in a sparkling bodysuit.

props.synopsis: Three Taylor Swift concerts in Vienna have been cancelled over fears of an apparent plot to launch an attack on an event in the Vienna area, such as the concerts.

title.children: Organisers cancel Taylor Swift concerts in Vienna over fears of an attack

image.altText: Separate close-up headshots of Tim Walz and JD Vance.

props.synopsis: Tim Walz, a conservative-looking progressive, has a backstory that is so quintessentially small-town America, it feels almost made up.

image.altText: Aerial shot of dozens of houses in neat rows in a new outer-suburban housing estate.

props.synopsis: The Reserve Bank governor's public declaration was intended to remove any expectation of rate relief for the remainder of this year. It's a reality check that landed with a thud.

title.children: The Reserve Bank governor has delivered a reality check on rates. It landed with a thud

image.altText: A portrait of Marcia Langton, an elderly Indigenous woman with long white hair, painted against a vivid indigo sky.

props.synopsis: Mounting scandals involving Buddhist monks are eroding public faith in a key pillar of Thai society.

image.altText: Screengrab of a grey-haired man being wrestled into a car by a few policeman

image.altText: A collection of Cosmos Magazine covers.

image.altText: Close up head shot of Elizabeth Taylor on a white backdrop

image.altText: Two drivers using a long implement to drill into a coral reef colony underwater

image.altText: A row of high rise buildings set in front of a blue sky.

image.altText: A board at the Australian Securities Exchange showing red and green stocks during trade.

props.synopsis: Qantas shares drop after former chief executive Alan Joyce's multi-million-dollar payout was cut by almost $10 million following a governance review. Follow the day's events and insights as they happen.

liveBlogKeyEvents.title: Reserve Bank governor Michele Bullock speaking in Armidale

image.altText: A female Australian water polo player wearing uniform cheers in Olympic swimming pool

props.synopsis: Here's everything that's going to be happening on day 13 of the Olympic Games.

title.children: Olympics schedule day 13: Stingers face the US, golf in full swing and boxers guaranteed to win medals

image.altText: George Mills, Vinesh Phogat and David Ahman

props.synopsis: An Indian wrestler was cruelly denied a shot at winning a gold medal, tempers flared as a cameraman caused chaos during the 5,000m heats and the Swedish men booked themselves into the volleyball medal rounds courtesy of a little-known move. Here are your quick hits from day 12 of the Paris Olympics.

title.children: Olympic quick hits: Heartbreak for Indian wrestler, cameraman wanders into a race and Sweden's crafty volleyball tactic

image.altText: Matt Wearn holds the Australian flag as he celebrates winning gold.

image.altText: Cyclists

image.altText: Hilary Caldwell, with long red hair and purple jumper, smiles widely. She is against a plain background.

props.synopsis: As a nurse, Hilary Caldwell had her community's respect, but when she became a sex worker at the age of 36 she felt she had to hide her career. Two decades on, she's decided to share her story.
